definition.value: A phosphate mineral with the general formula Ca5(PO4)3X where X = OH, F or Cl.
A phosphate mineral with the formula Ca5(PO4)3(OH).
A chemical substance that encourages a cell to commence cell division, triggering mitosis.
An ortho-fused compound in which at least one of the rings contains at least one heteroatom.
A compound with the general formula R2C=O (R=/=H) where one or more of the R groups contains an oxy (-O-) group.
An oxyketone with the general formula R2C(=O) (R=/=H) where one or more of the R groups contains an oxy (-O-) group and the oxy and carbonyl groups are bonded to the same carbon atom.
A compound based on an indole skeleton, containing one or more halogen atoms
An organobromine compound that is a compound based on an indole skeleton, containing one or more bromine atoms.
A glycolipid and which the glyco component is specified as galactosyl.
A diterpenoid with a tetracyclic skeleton.
A glycerol ether having at least one alkyl substituent on oxygen.
An sn-glycerophosphoserine compound having an acyl substituent at the 1-hydroxy position.
An inhibitor of ribonuclease H (EC 3.1.26.13), an enzyme required for specific hydrolysis of the RNA strand of an RNA/DNA hybrid.
An ethanolamine substituted at nitrogen by an acyl group.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerophosphoserine compound having an oleoyl substituent at the 1-hydroxy position.

L-Phenylalaninamide substituted at the amide nitrogen by a 1-(dihydroxyboranyl)-3-methylbutyl group and at N(alpha) by a pyrazin-2-ylcarbonyl group. It is a dipeptidyl boronic acid that reversibly inhibits the 26S proteasome.
A drug that blocks the action of proteasomes, cellular complexes that break down proteins.
A carbohydrate derivative in which the hydrogen atom of at least one alcoholic hydroxy group of a carbohydrate has been replaced by an acyl substituent.
An organic group that consists of a closed ring. It may be a substituent or a skeleton.
A cationic phosphosphingolipid consisting of sphingosine having a phosphocholine moiety attached to its primary hydroxyl group.
The biological role played by a material entity when bound by a receptor of the adaptive immune system. Specific site on an antigen to which an antibody binds.
An oxygenated derivative of cholesterol

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of lysine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of lysine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing lysine residues.
A halophenol in which the halogen atom is bonded to the carbon atom adjacent to the C-OH group.
The amino acid zwitterion formed from 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine by tranfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
A polymer carrying multiple negative charges.
Any fatty acid containing at least one C=C double bond.
A macromolecule containing ionic groups.

An EC 1.1.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of IMP dehydrogenase (EC 1.1.1.205), so blocking de novo biosynthesis of purine nucleotides.
An entity which inhibits the activity of HIV-1 reverse transcriptase.
A dipeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid units joined by a peptide linkage.

A 29-amino acid peptide hormone consisting of His, Ser, Gln, Gly, Thr, Phe, Thr, Ser, Asp, Tyr, Ser, Lys, Tyr, Leu, Asp, Ser, Arg, Arg, Ala, Gln, Asp, Phe, Val, Gln, Trp, Leu, Met, Asn and Thr residues joined in sequence.
An aldotriose comprising propanal having hydroxy groups at the 2- and 3-positions. It plays role in the formation of advanced glycation end-products (AGEs), a deleterious accompaniment to ageing.
A compound that exhibits agonist activity at the mu-opioid receptor.
A drug used for its effects on the gastrointestinal system, e.g. controlling gastric acidity, regulating gastrointestinal motility and water flow, and improving digestion.
A class of anticoagulants which act by inhibiting the action of vitamin K.
An imidazolidine containing one or more oxo groups.
A benzothiazole consisting of a benzene ring fused to an isothiazole.
A compound composed of a central piperidine structure with hydroxy and p-chlorophenyl substituents at position 4 and an N-linked p-fluorobutyrophenone moiety.
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
Tetraanion of coenzyme A.
An acyl-CoA(4-) that is the tetraanion of acetyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-leucine residues.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that is the pentaanion of succinyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid OH groups.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion that is the trianion of adenosine 5'-triphosphate arising from deprotonation of three of the four free triphosphate OH groups.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of glycine.
Pentaanion of (S)-methylmalonyl-CoA arising from deprotonation of phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid functions.
